{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488447"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:42:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:42:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"447"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/447"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.16,0.42,0.02,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112901"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/447"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94938"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1147"},{"type":"tags","id":"2066"},{"type":"tags","id":"2116"},{"type":"tags","id":"2117"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46378"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112901"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents with a six-month history of frequency, nocturia and a poor urinary stream. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. On digital rectal exam, his prostate and seminal vesicles feel firm and nodular with loss of the median sulcus. His PSA is 12.4 ng/mL (\u0026lt;4). A biopsy sample is taken and is graded as Gleason grade group 3 (Gleason score 4+3). A CT shows enlargement of the gland and the disease staged as T3b, N0, M0 with invasion of the seminal vesicles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["External beam radiotherapy (EBRT)","Androgen deprivation therapy (ADT)","Radical prostatectomy with extended pelvic lymph node dissection","Watchful Waiting","Active Surveillance"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe EAU risk group classification is used to classify patients with prostate cancer based on PSA, Gleason grade group and clinical staging on the risk of recurrence after treatment. Based on just the staging, the patient is classified to have high-risk locally advanced disease (T3b, N0, M0) regardless of the Gleason grade group or PSA .\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe concept of the Gleason grade group has now overtaken the Gleason score, as it is more accurate and simple to use. The lowest grade is 1 as opposed to a score of 6, which can potentially reduce overtreatment. It also allows a previous score of 7 to be differentiated into Gleason grade group 2 (3+4) and grade group 3 (4+3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor high-risk locally advanced disease, both treatment options of radical prostatectomy with extended pelvic lymph node dissection or external beam radiotherapy and long term ADT should be offered as primary treatment. Overall, no active treatment modality has shown to be superior over the others in terms of overall and prostate cancer-specific survival outcomes, hence men should be offered both modalities of treatment for localised disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical prostatectomy with extended pelvic lymph node dissection\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate answer due to the patient\u0027s high-risk disease. Furthermore, based on current evidence there is no consensus on whether an open, laparoscopic or robotic radical prostatectomy is superior to another.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is recommended that \u003Cstrong\u003EExternal beam radiotherapy (EBRT) \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be given in combination with long term ADT for high-risk disease, hence the option of EBRT alone is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAndrogen deprivation therapy (ADT)\u003C/strong\u003E is usually a component of neo-adjuvant or adjuvant therapy for carcinoma of the prostate, hence it is not used alone for curative intent. Its primary role is to treat metastatic prostate cancer, but it can also be used in combination with radiotherapy for high-risk localised of locally advanced disease. This approach should be offered to patients as well as surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the patient is symptomatic, and should have a life expectancy of more than 10 years with no other co-morbidities. Hence this palliative approach is inappropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the patient is classified as high-risk. Active surveillance should be offered if the patient is low-risk (PSA \u0026lt;10, T1-T2), and has a life expectancy of \u0026gt;10 years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Based on a life expectancy of greater or less than 10 years, a palliative or curative treatment approach should be decided between a multi-disciplinary team (urologists, radiation oncologists, medical oncologist, pathologists) and the patient.","Both surgical and radiotherapy options should be considered in patients with high -risk prostate cancer."],"references":["Mottet N, van den Bergh RC, Briers E, Van den Broeck T, Cumberbatch MG, et al. EAU-EANM-ESTRO-ESUR-SIOG guidelines on prostate cancer\u20142020 update. Part 1: screening, diagnosis, and local treatment with curative intent. Eur urol. 2021;79(2):243-62. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33172724/","Epstein JI, Zelefsky MJ, Sjoberg DD, Nelson JB, Egevad L, Magi-Galluzzi C, et al. A contemporary prostate cancer grading system: A validated alternative to the Gleason score. Eur urol. 2016;69(3):428-35. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5002992/","Homewood D, Lucas H, Kennedy C, et al. When less is more:  Updates in active  surveillance and watchful  waiting in the management  of prostate cancer. AJGP 2024; 53."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94938"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"447"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94938"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-07T17:18:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-07T17:19:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"447"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112901"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"